  "prompt": "How is residual volume calculated?",
  "response": "Residual volume (RV) is the amount of air remaining in the lungs after a maximum exhalation. It can be calculated through several methods:\n\n1. Helium Dilution Technique\n- Patient breathes a known volume of helium in a closed system\n- Allows calculation of lung volume by measuring helium concentration changes\n- Based on gas dilution principle\n\n2. Nitrogen Washout Method\n- Patient breathes 100% oxygen\n- Measures nitrogen concentration during exhalation\n- Calculates remaining lung volume based on nitrogen elimination\n\n3. Body Plethysmography\n- Most accurate direct measurement method\n- Patient sits in a sealed body box\n- Measures lung volume changes by pressure and volume relationships\n- Provides precise residual volume measurement\n\n4. Radiographic Estimation\n- Uses chest X-rays or CT scans\n- Estimates lung volume through imaging techniques\n- Less precise than direct measurement methods\n\n5. Computational Formulas\n- Uses predicted values based on age, height, sex, and body composition\n- Provides estimated residual volume\n- Less accurate than direct measurement techniques\n\nEach method has specific advantages and limitations in measuring residual volume.",
